<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; [Duplicate message snipped]</font></pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='24390#1425625383'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2015-03-06T07:03:03+00:00">Mar 6, 2015 07:03 AM UTC</time> by <b>OSG-GOC</b><a class="anchor" name="1425625383">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Please assign this critical priority ticket to NOvA.  I have already begun a discussion with the NOvA liaison by email but my department head asked me to make it a GOC ticket.

Can NOvA please remove the nova_v07 flux files from oasis urgently today?  Its presence is currently blocking all oasis repository updates to the FNAL stratum 1 and will until at least Sunday.  The oasis repository currently contains software from many different VOs including belle, csiu, glow, and microboone.  All cvmfs clients that are geographically closest to FNAL get their files from the FNAL stratum 1.  More technical details are below.

On Tuesday, NOvA published nova_v07 flux files in the oasis CVMFS repository that resulted in the addition of 450GB of space.  In addition to bringing the oasis system at the GOC to a crawl for about 36 hours as it fed the updates to 8 Stratum 1s (6 production, 2 test), one of the Stratum 1s (NIKHEF) ran out of disk space (so they deleted the whole repository) and another (FNAL) came very close to running out of space until I stopped the update.  I found out on Thursday from the BNL Stratum 1 administrator that the cms.cern.ch repository could be compacted to save 600GB, however in order to do that it requires at least 300GB of scratch space and a lot of time as it makes a copy. I began that compaction 8 hours ago on the FNAL backup stratum 1, and so far it is less than 20% finished.  After that it will need to be copied from the backup stratum 1 to the primary, so I do not expect that oasis updates could be reenabled until at least Sunday.

For the future, there is new much more capable stratum 1 hardware at Fermilab with much more disk space that has been delivered but not yet installed by DCSO.

In my strong technical opinion, flux files (which are ROOT format) do not belong in ordinary CVMFS at all.  I have a research project trying to show that CVMFS could be used for such &#34;auxiliary data&#34; files, but only in a different configuration that uses no squids and instead configures the cvmfs clients to cache their files on a high speed storage element such as dCache using a feature cvmfs calls &#34;alien cache&#34;.  Meanwhile can NOvA themselves please access these files only on such storage elements?

by /DC=com/DC=DigiCert-Grid/O=Open Science Grid/OU=People/CN=Dave Dykstra 508</pre></div><legend>Similar Recent Tickets <small>modified within the last 30 days</small></legend><div id="similar_tickets"><p class="muted">No similar tickets found.</p></div>
